have been decorated!

âNot that I value the decoration,â Roudier said to Granoux, whom he had
dragged into the embrasure of a window. âI refused it in the time of
Louis-Philippe, when I was purveyor to the court. Ah! Louis-Philippe was
a good king. France will never find his equal!â

Roudier was becoming an Orleanist once more. And he added, with the
crafty hypocrisy of an old hosier from the Rue Saint-Honore: âBut you,
my dear Granoux; donât you think the ribbon would look well in your
